THE BALLOTS ARE NOW OPEN! If you are interested in being part of the ASU Executive Team for the 2024-2025 academic year now is your chance! The nomination period is open starting now, until Tuesday, May 21st at 11:59 P.M. 

If you have any questions about the roles or the election, please feel free to send us a message! We will also be answering any inquiries at the End of Year Barbecue taking place on May 16th at Downsview Park.

Hey hey hey! Are you interested in being part of the ASU? Do you absolutely love all the hard work we’ve done to bring you amazing opportunities? Have you shown up to every single event and thought to yourself, “Wow what a great team, I hope I can be a part of it someday”?

Curious about how research at UTIAS is changing offroad robotics? 🚜 Discover how PhD student Alexander Krawciw is paving the way for smarter, safer autonomous systems in unpredictable terrains, earning him the prestigious Vanier Canada Graduate Scholarship. ⁠
⁠
His journey, under the mentorship of Professor Tim Barfoot, showcases the power of dedication in his field. Visit our bio link to read about what Krawciw is most excited for in his PhD program.⁠
⁠
⁠
#PhDJourney #AutonomousRobotics #MachineLearning #RoboticsResearch #UTIAS #EngineeringInnovation #universityoftoronto

Congratulations to Professor Clinton Groth for being selected as the recipient of @uoftengineering's Joint Seed Program. 🌌 ⁠
⁠
Groth's research in radiation magnetohydrodynamics promises to shed new light on the intricate emissions of #blackholes, unveiling parallels with solar phenomena. This endeavor, undertaken in collaboration with Bart Ripperda, holds immense potential to deepen our understanding of astrophysical systems and their interactions with the #cosmos. ⁠
⁠
⁠
#researchgrant #computationalfluiddynamics #propulsion #theoreticalphysics

Can self-driving cars see around corners? 🚙 Professor Waslander and his team at UTIAS are developing a new kind of AI for self-driving cars. This AI, called SWTrack, can predict what pedestrians and cyclists will do next, even when they are hidden from sight. SWTrack uses information from the past five seconds to create a better picture of what's going on around the car, allowing it to make safer decisions. Learn more in our bio link about how our researchers are revolutionizing self-driving cars.

A satellite, built and operated by #UofTEngineering students, launched into orbit on a Falcon 9 rocket. Learn how the @uoft_aerospaceteam’s Space Systems division achieved this feat with the HERON Mk. II and their plans for the next launch: link in @uoftengineering’s bio.

Images in this carousel:

1) HERON’s ground station on the sixth-floor roof of the Bahen Centre.

2) Reid Sox-Harris performing electrical work for the ground station.

3 & 4) From left to right, the evolution of HERON: HERON Mk. I (2016), HERON Mk. II Prototype (2018), HERON Mk. II Softstack (2020), HERON Mk. II Flight Model (2021).

5) Members of the UTAT Space Systems division gather on the sixth-floor roof of the Bahen Centre with the fully assembled ground station.

6) A Falcon 9 rocket lifts off from Vandenberg Space Force Base on November 11. (Photo: SpaceX)

Winter vibes in the world of aerospace – where innovation meets frosty inspiration. ❄️⁠
⁠
⁠
⁠
#UTIAS #UofTStudentLife #UofT #WhoDoWeCredit

You might want to learn about Canada's first fully student-funded and student-developed satellite mission, HERON Mk. II. ✨⁠
⁠
On November 11, 2023, HERON Mk. II, a 3U CubeSat built by @uoft_aerospaceteam, soared into space aboard a @SpaceX #Falcon9 rocket. Witnessing the culmination of years of hard work, Benjamin Nero (UTIAS MASc candidate) shared the experience as HERON's mission manager as “surreal”. ⁠
⁠
This achievement involved over 100 students. Despite challenges, the team was undeterred to fulfill HERON Mk. II’s primary mission: to demonstrate UTAT’s radio communications capabilities, while secondary objectives are to include validating the structural, thermal, power, and computing system designs. 🛰️ ⁠
⁠
The journey continues with HERON's ground-breaking success paving the way for UTAT's next mission, FINCH, set to launch in late 2025. Learn more in our bio link. 🌐⁠
⁠
Photos courtesy of SpaceX and UTAT.⁠
⁠
#SpaceXLaunch #StudentInnovation #CubeSat #UTIAS #SpaceExploration #StudentAchievement

UTIAS teams up with @siemens to develop sustainable propulsion and power generation. 🔋 ⁠
⁠
Led by Professor S. Chaudhuri, the research redefines gas turbine engines, aiming to reduce carbon emissions in aviation and fuel consumption. By tackling the challenges of transitioning to sustainable energy sources, they will build a comprehensive understanding that will guide the creation of fuel-flex gas turbine engines. ⁠
⁠
To learn more about this collaboration bridging academia and industry, click on the bio link in our profile.
